However, since we are asked to solve the problem without using loops or recursion, we can use bitwise operations to check if n is a power of three.

The key observation is that any number n which is a power of three has the binary representation of the form 1.x...x1010101... (where x is 0 or 1). This is because 3 raised to the power of any positive integer is always congruent to 1 modulo 8 (since 3^2 = 9 = 1 modulo 8). Therefore, the binary representation of a number n which is a power of three will have exactly two 1's in every group of three bits starting from the least significant bit.

We can check this property using bitwise operations as follows:

1. Convert n to its binary representation using the Integer.toBinaryString() method.
2. Check if the binary representation of n has exactly two 1's in every group of three bits starting from the least significant bit.

Here's the Java code to implement the above solution:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) return false;
        String binary = Integer.toBinaryString(n);
        for (int i = binary.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (binary.charAt(i) == '0') {
                int group = i - (i % 3);
                if (binary.charAt(group) != '1') {
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

